  "planned_workouts": [
    {
      "id": 100896223,
      "date": "2026-03-28",
      "name": "Mallorca Simulation Lite \u2014 Discipline Climbing Reference",
      "type": "WORKOUT",
      "sport_type": "Ride",
      "planned_tss": 250,
      "duration_hours": 5.25,
      "duration_formatted": "5h15m",
      "workout_summary": null,
      "description": "SATURDAY OBJECTIVE: discipline, not heroics. 86 km / ~2137 m climbing reference route.\n\nPACING RULES\n- Flats/rolling before climbs: 60-72% FTP, keep it conversational.\n- Main climbs: cap steady work at 76-88% FTP. Short ramps may touch 90-95% FTP for <60s, then return under control.\n- Absolute rule: no sustained threshold efforts, no ego surges, no chasing segment fantasies.\n- Descents: full recovery, eat and drink.\n\nHEART RATE GUARDRAILS\n- Aerobic ceiling most of the day: <83% LTHR (~<138 bpm).\n- On longer climbs: allow brief drift into high aerobic / low tempo, but avoid sitting above ~145-148 bpm for long stretches.\n- If HR is unusually high early for ordinary power: back off.\n\nFUEL / HYDRATION\n- Start fed.\n- 80-90 g carbs/hour.\n- 500-750 ml/hour, more if warm.\n- Eat early, not after the damage is done.\n\nEXECUTION CHECKS\n- First 90 min should feel almost too easy.\n- If legs feel amazing, ignore them.\n- If repeated climbs require >90% FTP just to hold rhythm, you are overcooking it.\n- If by hour 4 power fades but HR remains stable and pacing stays controlled, that is acceptable fatigue.\n\nPOST-RIDE INTENT\n- This is a reference workout for comparing planned vs actual pacing, intensity distribution, HR drift, and discipline under climbing load."
    },
    {
      "id": 100916378,
      "date": "2026-03-29",
      "name": "Fatigue Resistance Endurance Reference",
      "type": "WORKOUT",
      "sport_type": "Ride",
      "planned_tss": 145,
      "duration_hours": 3.5,
      "duration_formatted": "3h30m",
      "workout_summary": null,
      "description": "SUNDAY OBJECTIVE: controlled endurance on tired legs. This is the day after the climbing simulation, so the goal is durability and fatigue resistance, not a second hard session.\n\nPACING RULES\n- Ride mostly at 62-75% FTP.\n- First hour: strictly easy aerobic, keep pressure low and cadence smooth.\n- Middle block: settle into honest endurance, but avoid drifting into tempo just because the legs wake up.\n- Final hour: stay steady. If good legs remain, hold upper Z2 only; do NOT turn it into a progression ride.\n\nHEART RATE GUARDRAILS\n- Normal target: stay under ~83% LTHR (~<138 bpm).\n- Brief rises on rollers are fine, but if HR keeps climbing while power stays ordinary, back off.\n- If fatigue is real and legs are dull, that is acceptable; protect the aerobic purpose.\n\nEXECUTION CHECKS\n- This ride should look cleaner than it feels.\n- Minimal surging, minimal ego, minimal grey-zone leakage.\n- If Saturday was harder than planned, shorten to 150-180 min and keep it fully aerobic.\n\nFUEL / HYDRATION\n- 60-80 g carbs/hour.\n- 500-750 ml/hour.\n- Start eating early; tired legs plus low glycogen is just fake heroism.\n\nPOST-RIDE INTENT\n- Reference workout for comparing actual endurance durability after Saturday load: pacing stability, HR behavior, decoupling, and discipline under fatigue."
    },
